===Etymology 1===
From {{inh|en|enm|beggen}}, assimilation from {{etyl|ang|en}} {{m|ang|*becgan}}, {{m|ang|*bedcan}}, {{m|ang|*bedican}}, syncopated variants of {{inh|en|ang|bedecian||to beg}}, perhaps from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*bedagô||petitioner; requestor; beggar}}, from {{m|gem-pro|*bedą}}, {{m|gem-pro|*bedō||prayer; request}}. Related to {{cog|frr|bēdagi||to pray}}, {{cog|got|𐌱𐌹𐌳𐌰𐌲𐍅𐌰||beggar}}, {{cog|ang|biddan||to ask}}. More at {{l|en|bid}}, {{l|en|bead}}.

====Verb====
{{en-verb|begg}}

# {{lb|en|intransitive}} to request the help of someone, often in the form of money
#: ''He '''begged''' on the street corner from passers-by.''
# {{lb|en|transitive}} to [[plead]] with someone for help, a favor, etc.; to [[entreat]]
#: ''I '''beg''' your pardon. I didn't mean to cause offence.''
#: ''He '''begged''' her to go to the prom with him''.
#* Shakespeare
#*: I do '''beg''' your good will in this case.
#* Bible, Matthew xxvii. 58
#*: [Joseph] '''begged''' the body of Jesus.
#* '''1898''', {{w|J. Meade Falkner}}, {{w|Moonfleet}} Chapter 5
#*: But that same day came Sam Tewkesbury to the Why Not? about nightfall, and '''begged''' a glass of rum, being, as he said, 'all of a shake'{{...}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} to assume, in the phrase {{m|en|beg the question}}
# {{lb|en|proscribed}} to [[raise]] a question, in the phrase {{m|en|beg the question}}
# {{lb|en|legal|obsolete}} To ask to be appointed guardian for, or to ask to have a guardian appointed for.
#* Harrington
#*: Else some will '''beg''' thee, in the court of wards.

